The paper presents a new method for learning a conditional distribution given some input variables based on a conditional maximum mean discrepancy (CMMD) criterion. This method is evaluated on a wide range of tasks, including predictive modeling, contextual generation, and Bayesian dark knowledge. These tasks are all related to machine learning and artificial intelligence, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves image generation and processing, which could also place it in the cs.CV (Computer Vision) sub-category. The use of back-propagation and stochastic gradient descent for learning suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves Bayesian modeling and knowledge distillation, which could place it in the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.SD (Sound) sub-categories, respectively.
